7.31.1.description:
https://forum.babylonjs.com/t/outline-post-process/50488

I wrote this article with my different accout.

This PR adds a new EdgeDetectionPostProcess to BabylonJS.
This post-process applies an edge detection effect based on normals and depth buffers from the geometry buffer renderer, providing developers with a versatile way to highlight object outlines.

Key Features
Configurable edge color, width, and intensity for flexible stylization.
Supports different render modes:

General
Normal
Depth
Only Outline
Uses Geometry Buffer Renderer to access normals and depth textures for precise edge detection.

Why this is needed?
This post-process enhances the visual rendering capabilities of BabylonJS by allowing developers to add stylized edge detection, which is commonly used in cartoon rendering, technical visualizations, and architectural previews.

How to Use
Enable the geometry buffer renderer and apply the post-process:

// edge detection post process
const edgeDetectionPP = new BABYLON.EdgeDetectionPostProcess("", scene, 1, camera);
edgeDetectionPP.samples = 4;
// Defines the intensity of the detected edges. Higher values result in more pronounced edges.
edgeDetectionPP.edgeIntensity = .3;
// Defines the width of the detected edges. Higher values result in thicker edges.
edgeDetectionPP.edgeWidth = .2;
// Defines the color of the detected edges
edgeDetectionPP.edgeColor = new BABYLON.Color3(0, 0, 0);


https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/f988c4cf-aef2-4ff3-a3de-0bdcf804631d

7.27.2.description:
PG to use to test: #5SPY1V#5


Relevant code:
```
scene.customRenderFunction = () => {
            // Clear back buffer
            engine.clear(new BABYLON.Color4(0, 0.3, 0.5, 1), true, true);

            // Update view and projection matrices based on active camera
            scene.updateTransformMatrix();

            // Set viewport size
            engine.setViewport(camera.viewport);

            // Compute world matrix and render
            for (let index = 0; index < scene.meshes.length; index++) {
                const mesh = scene.meshes[index];

                if (!mesh.material) {
                    continue;
                }

                mesh.computeWorldMatrix();

                if (mesh.material.needAlphaBlending()) {
                    engine.setAlphaMode(BABYLON.Constants.ALPHA_COMBINE);
                } else {
                    engine.setAlphaMode(BABYLON.Constants.ALPHA_DISABLE);
                }
                mesh.directRender();
            }
        }
```

7.20.0.description:
This is an alternative approach to https://github.com/BabylonJS/Babylon.js/pull/15222. Compared to the original approach, this one:
1. Has a simpler implementation and has a smaller impact on the API surface.
1. Is slightly less type safe when adding new loader plugins or glTF extensions.
1. Is much simpler for the caller.

With this approach, options are a type safe plain object with no factory functions. Invocation looks like this (for example):
```ts
await SceneLoader.LoadAssetContainerAsync("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BabylonJS/Assets/master/meshes/LevelOfDetail.glb", scene, {
  onProgress: (event) => { },
  pluginOptions: {
    gltf: {
      loadOnlyMaterials: true,
      extensionOptions: {
        MSFT_lod: {
          maxLODsToLoad: 5,
        },
        MSFT_minecraftMesh: {
          enabled: false,
        },
      },
    },
  },
});
```

This works by simply allowing plugins and extensions to augment the options interface, such that when you import a plugin or extension, it augments the options interface with options specific to the plugin or extension. From the consumer's standpoint, this is fully type safe, so you get clear intellisense showing you exactly how the options can be configured.

I only implemented options for glTF in this PR, not any other loaders.

This is how it shows up with intellisense in VS Code:
![image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/b98ce86b-2f5e-48cb-a9cc-6b4b14464059)
![image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/d169d3f8-c5ba-4d07-bb2f-5331905e348e)

@deltakosh, @sebavan, @bghgary

This PR makes `Vector3` work with `Vector3LikeInternal`, a new interface. The idea is that this is now valid:
```ts
const vec3 = new Vector3();

vec3.addInPlace({ _x: 1, _y: 2, _z: 3 });

const half = vec3.divide({ _x: 2, _y: 2, _z: 2 });
```

The necessary inlining of some `copyFrom` and `copyFromFloats` calls should speed up performance as well.

This was discussed in a [form post](https://forum.babylonjs.com/t/52593/26?u=vortex).

This PR condenses the exporting of `Epsilon` with its definition:

```diff
/**
 * Constant used to define the minimal number value in Babylon.js
 * @ignorenaming
 */
// eslint-disable-next-line @typescript-eslint/naming-convention
-const Epsilon = 0.001;
-export { Epsilon };
+export const Epsilon = 0.001;

```

7.13.3.description:
This PR introduces the public package build for the alpha viewer that was previously introduced in this PR: https://github.com/BabylonJS/Babylon.js/pull/15241

The overall strategy is summarized in the comment at the top of the `prepublish.cjs` script:
```js
// The alpha version of the viewer package must have a unique package name within the context of the mono repo / npm workspace
// as long as the legacy version is still being maintained and published. Therefore, the alpha package has a unique name, but this
// is not the actual name we want to publish it under. This script copies the name and version from the legacy package.json to the
// alpha package.json, appends "-alpha" to the version, and removes the private flag, scripts, and devDependencies from the alpha,
// and finally deletes the legacy package.json. This script should be run after the alpha package has been built and before it is
// published. This script is not necessary when the legacy package is deprecated and the alpha package is published under the same
// name as the legacy package.
```

Given this, the high level aspects of this new folder are:
- Includes a rollup based build that bundles everything into a single file but still uses esm (webpack is good at creating umd bundle files, but not esm bundle files).
  - Bundling to esm allows us to not "ship our directory structure," which gives us the freedom to update the directory structure or file names in the viewer source without creating back compat issues.
  - It also bundles the d.ts files into a single d.ts
  - Later when we introduce dynamic imports, it won't be one bundle file but rather a handful. Technically people could import the dynamic import bundles, but it's unlikely someone would do so since rollup basically gives them random names.
- Includes a prepublish.cjs script that modifies the package.json and deletes the legacy viewer package.json so the new alpha viewer can be published with the same name (with the `-alpha` version suffix).

Separately, @RaananW (or me with @RaananW's help) will modify the CI build to run this prepublish step and then specifically publish the new alpha viewer package. That will come in a different PR.

I also had to make a few changes to the actual viewer source code to get this all working (tested a local build of the package in a vanilla-ts Vite project).

7.13.1.description:
Before:
``` js
refreshBoundingInfo(applySkeleton: boolean, applyMorph: boolean)
```

After:
``` js
export interface IMeshDataOptions {
    applySkeleton?: boolean;
    applyMorph?: boolean;
    updatePositionsArray?: boolean;
    cache?: IMeshDataCache;
}

refreshBoundingInfo(options: IMeshDataOptions)
```

The `updatePositionsArray` flag will allow users to disable computing this array which isn't used in all situations.
The `cache` object will cache the allocations, reduce `slice` calls, etc.

On my machine:
[Before](https://playground.babylonjs.com/#B8B8Z2#5): 2.81s
[After](http://localhost:1338/#B8B8Z2#61): 1.67s

